"But, Ernest," replied the soldier, "we kill decently;
                  we don't rob a fellow of all that makes life worth having, and then worry or
                  starve him to death!"

"You flatter me, lady—highly honor me in even reading one of my poor productions;
                  but if I have been so fortunate as to interest you in the fate of a pictured one
                  of our city unfortunates, I am doubly flattered!"

The heart of Cramer beat wildly beneath her glance, as she spoke then, and he felt
                  that there was a deeper expression in her look than there was in her words merely;
                  an expression which awakened a tumult of hopes and wishes in his heart.

"Neow, mister, dew tell me what this 'ere is. Yeou know 'em;
                  aint—aint they m-a-r-i-e-d? If they wasn't, it would be awful, for
                  our house is the decentest tavern in the county."

"Not without they're called out; they're in their room, and there's a bolt inside;
                  but I could hollow fire, or raise a scream; maybe that would bring 'em
                     eout! Shall I?"

"What!" murmured the girl in astonishment, as the soldier passed haughtily on;
                  "are his friends false? God help him! God help him! Oh, that I had
                  not sworn; but my father forced me to swear. I will not aid them—no, never!"

"Stay, child!" said the priest, sternly. "Stay, I command thee, and hear all! The
                  end justifieth the deed—in this matter the Church will justify and absolve thee,
                  and his marriage to thee will take away all stain before men.'
